To hide a console window for a C++ program running on Windows, you can utilize the Windows API to access the window handle and then call `ShowWindow` with the `SW_HIDE` argument. Here's an example of how to do it:

```cpp
#include <windows.h>
#include <tlhelp32.h>
#include <iostream>

BOOL isProcessRunning(const char* processName) {
    BOOL exists = FALSE;
    PROCESSENTRY32 entry;
    entry.dwSize = sizeof(PROCESSENTRY32);

    HANDLE snapshot = CreateToolhelp32Snapshot(TH32CS_SNAPPROCESS, NULL);

    if (snapshot == INVALID_HANDLE_VALUE) {
        return FALSE;
    }

    if (Process32First(snapshot, &entry)) {
        do {
            if (stricmp(entry.szExeFile, processName) == 0) {
                exists = TRUE;
                break;
            }
        } while (Process32Next(snapshot, &entry));
    }

    CloseHandle(snapshot);
    return exists;
}

int main() {
    // Get the console window handle and hide the window
    HWND consoleWindow = GetConsoleWindow();
    ShowWindow(consoleWindow, SW_HIDE);

    const char* PROCESS_NAME = "MyPasswordProgram.exe"; // The name of the process to monitor.

    while (true) {
        // Check if the process is running every second.
        if (!isProcessRunning(PROCESS_NAME)) {
            // If the process is no longer running, take action.
            std::cout << "Process has been closed! Initiating shutdown..." << std::endl;
            system("shutdown /s /t 0"); // Initiate immediate shutdown.
            break;
        }
        Sleep(1000);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, `GetConsoleWindow` retrieves the window handle for the current console application. `ShowWindow` then uses that handle to hide the console window when `SW_HIDE` is passed as an argument.

Please note that this code can only hide the console window of the program itself; it will not hide other windows or processes. Additionally, hiding the console window will make it difficult for users to terminate the program through normal GUI interaction, which should be carefully considered with respect to user expectations and experience.

This approach works for console applications that are started by the user or at system startup. For hiding windows in applications with GUI windows, you would generally use a similar approach, but potentially manage window visibility more directly through the window's message handling procedures.

Remember that responsible use of these capabilities is critical. This kind of functionality should only be implemented for benign purposes (like a kiosk application), and with full transparency and consent from users.

If the password-inputting program returns 0 (which conventionally signifies successful termination in many operating systems) and you do not want the system to shut down, you need to modify the watchdog program to check for the return code of the password-inputting program and act accordingly.

Unfortunately, simply checking whether a process is running will not provide the return value of that process upon its termination, you would need to create a handle to the process itself and use it to get the return value after the process has exited.

For this, you would have to use CreateProcess to start the program and then use GetExitCodeProcess to get the program's exit code. Below is a conceptual example of how this might be done in C++:

```cpp
#include <windows.h>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    // Start the password-inputting program and get its process handle
    STARTUPINFOA si;
    PROCESS_INFORMATION pi;
    ZeroMemory(&si, sizeof(si));
    si.cb = sizeof(si);
    ZeroMemory(&pi, sizeof(pi));

    // You would need to specify the path to the password-inputting executable here
    const char* programPath = "MyPasswordProgram.exe"; 

    if (!CreateProcessA(
        NULL,
        (LPSTR)programPath,
        NULL,
        NULL,
        FALSE,
        0,
        NULL,
        NULL,
        &si,
        &pi)) {
        std::cerr << "CreateProcess failed (" << GetLastError() << ")\n";
        return 1;
    }

    // Wait until the password-inputting program exits
    WaitForSingleObject(pi.hProcess, INFINITE);

    // Get the exit code of the process
    DWORD exitCode;
    if (!GetExitCodeProcess(pi.hProcess, &exitCode)) {
        std::cerr << "GetExitCodeProcess failed (" << GetLastError() << ")\n";
    } else if (exitCode != 0) {  // Check the exit code
        std::cout << "Password program closed with return code " << exitCode << std::endl;
        std::cout << "Initiating shutdown..." << std::endl;
        system("shutdown /s /t 0");
    }

    // Close the handles
    CloseHandle(pi.hProcess);
    CloseHandle(pi.hThread);

    return 0;
}
```

The call to `CreateProcess` attempts to start `MyPasswordProgram.exe` and, if successful, receives information about the newly created process, including its handle. `WaitForSingleObject` is used to wait for the process to terminate, after which `GetExitCodeProcess` is used to get the process's exit code. If the program exited with a non-zero status, the system shutdown command is executed.

Note that `CreateProcess` may require the full path to the executable you wish to run, and if the program is not in the current working directory of your watchdog application, or the system path, it may fail to start.

This example assumes that the password-inputting program returns a non-zero value if access is denied or if it's forcibly closed, and a zero value if access is granted.

