To set a time limit for a user to input a password in C++, you can use multithreading with a condition variable or other synchronization mechanism to wait for input for a certain duration. Below is an example that uses `<thread>`, `<mutex>`, and `<condition_variable>` from the C++11 standard library to achieve this.

Please note that the following example is a simple console application and does not mask the password input. If you want to create a more secure password prompt that doesn't echo characters to the console, you'd need a platform-specific solution like `_getch()` in Windows or `termios` on Unix-like systems.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>
#include <condition_variable>
#include <chrono>

std::mutex mtx;
std::condition_variable cv;
bool finished_input = false;

void readPassword(std::string& password) {
    std::cout << "Please input the password. You have 10 seconds: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, password);
    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);
        finished_input = true;
    }
    cv.notify_one();
}

int main() {
    std::string password;

    // Start thread to read password from input
    std::thread input_thread(readPassword, std::ref(password));

    {
        std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(mtx);
        if (cv.wait_for(lock, std::chrono::seconds(10), [] { return finished_input; })) {
            // User finished input within 10 seconds
            std::cout << "\nYour input was received in time: " << password << std::endl;
        } else {
            // Time limit exceeded
            std::cout << "\nTime limit exceeded. No input received." << std::endl;
        }
    }

    input_thread.join(); // Make sure to join the thread

    // You would typically check the password here
    // and take appropriate action based on whether it's correct

    return 0;
}
```

In this code:

1. The `main()` function starts a `std::thread` to handle user input so that the main thread can continue to enforce the time limit.
2. In the `readPassword` function, we wait for the user's password input using `std::getline()`.
3. If the user enters a password before the timeout, we set a boolean flag `finished_input` to true and notify the main thread using a condition variable.
4. The main thread waits on the condition variable for up to 10 seconds. If `finished_input` becomes true within this time (indicating the user has finished entering their password), the program proceeds; otherwise, it informs the user that the time limit has been exceeded.

The program presented here is a simple, platform-independent console application. For a real-world application, especially one handling sensitive information like passwords, you would need to consider a more secure approach to password handling and user interaction.

To verify if the inputted password is correct, you typically compare the user-provided password against a pre-defined value. In a real-world application, this value would be a hashed password stored securely, not a plaintext password written into the code.

Below is the previous example, but with an additional check to verify if the password is correct. For the purpose of this example, I'm using a plaintext password, but please remember that in a secure application, you should never store passwords in plaintext. Always use password hashing with a salt and compare the hashed input with the stored hash.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>
#include <condition_variable>
#include <chrono>

std::mutex mtx;
std::condition_variable cv;
bool finished_input = false;

// For simplicity, the "correct" password is stored in plaintext.
// In a real application, you should NEVER store passwords in plaintext.
// Always hash and salt passwords, and compare against the hashed version.
const std::string CORRECT_PASSWORD = "MySecurePassword";

void readPassword(std::string& password) {
    std::cout << "Please input the password. You have 10 seconds: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, password);
    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mtx);
        finished_input = true;
    }
    cv.notify_one();
}

int main() {
    std::string password;

    // Start thread to read password from input
    std::thread input_thread(readPassword, std::ref(password));

    {
        std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lock(mtx);
        if (cv.wait_for(lock, std::chrono::seconds(10), [] { return finished_input; })) {
            // User finished input within 10 seconds
            std::cout << "Your input was received in time.\n";

            // Check if the entered password is correct
            if (password == CORRECT_PASSWORD) {
                std::cout << "Password is correct! Access granted.\n";
            } else {
                std::cout << "Incorrect password! Access denied.\n";
            }
        } else {
            // Time limit exceeded
            std::cout << "Time limit exceeded. No input received.\n";
        }
    }

    input_thread.join(); // Make sure to join the thread

    return 0;
}
```

In this modified version, we check if the inputted password matches `CORRECT_PASSWORD`. If there's a match, we grant access; otherwise, we deny it.

For a secure application, you would use a cryptographic hash function, such as SHA-256, along with a unique salt for each password. The salt would be stored alongside the hashed password, and when verifying, you would hash the input password with the same salt and compare it to the stored hash.

Keep in mind that proper password handling and security best practices are complex topics that involve considerations beyond the scope of this simple example. Always ensure privacy and security compliance when dealing with user authentication.
